 improving</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> instrument traceability.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ndividuals deemed to be “at increased risk” of CJD</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> are those</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> individuals who, broadly, have received blood or been operated on with certain surgical instruments, from someone with CJD and are deemed to have had sufficient proba</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">bility of acquiring the disease thems</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">elves that they could, in their</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> turn transmit disease via surgery or blood transfusion.  They are thus deferred from blood donation and special arrangements need to be made for surgery that involves tissues in which </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">PrP</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> infectivity is expected to be found.  Advice from local public health or infection control teams</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> is recommended</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in the first instance and th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ose local teams are advised</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to seek more expert help, usually via the CJD Section of the National Centre for Infect</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ious Disease Surveillance and Control of Public Health England that acts as a clearing house for queries and can link them with the UK’s various speci