><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Even though </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rion</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> proteins are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ubiquitous in nature</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, outbreaks of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">prion</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> diseases, whether in humans or animals, have always been unexpected</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  Quite apart from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">v</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">CJD</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and BSE, other examples include the current unexplained spread of Chronic Wasting Disease of Mule Deer and Elk (CWD) in Nor</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">th America, Transmissible Mink Encephalopathy in America in the 1940s and the extension of sheep </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">scrapie</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in Britain in the 1930s (thought</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">retrospectively</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span